1. Introduction¶

PID controller is a widely used industrial control system. PID stands for "proportional integral derivative". In our project, we are using PID controller to design a trajectory for a vehicle.

The optimization problem we are addressing is that we have a planned trajectory for a vehicle that is at a specific location and speed. This vehicle's speed is controlled by its acceleration, which is in turn contingent on the three parameters of the PID controller, i.e., $k_P$, $k_I$, and $k_D$. Our goal is to find the optimal parameters that lead to the minimal differences between the planned trajectory and the actual trajectory.

Here is our problem:

The planned trajectory starts from location 0 at time 0. It is cruising at 30m/s speed for the first 10 seconds, then decreasing to 10 m/s with deceleration $2m/s^2$ for 10 seconds and then accelerating to 30m/s with acceleration $2m/s^2$ for 10 seconds, and then cruising at 30 m/s for 20 seconds.

The actual location is 3 at time 0 and the actual speed is 28m/s at time 0.

Assuming the acceleration cannot be precisely controlled, and always has a random error uniformly distributed over $[0.2,0.2]m/s$

2. Mathematical model¶

2.A. Variables¶

We have the following decision variables:

  • $0 \le k_P \le 10$
  • $0 \le k_I \le 100$
  • $0 \le k_D \le 1000$

These three are the key PID controller parameters.

We also have:

  • $T$: the time span
  • $\delta$: time interval
  • $\epsilon$: random error in acceleration control
  • $a_P$: a vector
  • $a_I$: a vector
  • $a_D$: a vector
  • $a$: acceleration at each timestamp, a vector
  • $x$: the location of the actual vehicle at each timestamp, a vector
  • $y$: the position of the planned trajectory at each timestamp, a vector
  • $vx$: the velocity of the actual vehile at each timestamp, a vector
  • $vy$: the velocity of the planned trajector at each timestamp, a vector
  • $int_x$: the integral of $x$ at each timestamp, a vector
  • $int_y$: the integral of $y$ at each timestamp, a vector

2.B. Constraints¶

A each timestamp $t \ge \delta$, we have the following dynamics, or contraints:

$$a_{P_{t}} = k_{P_{t}} (y_t - x_t)$$$$a_{I_{t}} = k_{I_{t}} (int_{y_{t}} - int_{x_{t}})$$$$a_{D_{t}} = k_{D_{t}} (vy_t - vx_t)$$$$a_t = a_{P_{t}} + a_{I_{t}} + a_{D_{t}} + \epsilon$$$$vx_t = vx_{t-\delta} + \delta \cdot a_{t-\delta}$$$$x_t = x_{t_\delta} + 0.5(vx_t + vx_{t-\delta}) \delta$$$$int_{x_{t}} = int_{x_{t-\delta}} + x_t \delta$$$$y_t = y_{t_\delta} + 0.5(vy_t + vy_{t-\delta}) \delta$$$$int_{y_{t}} = int_{y_{t-\delta}} + y_t \delta$$

2.C. Objective function¶

The objective function is least squares. We want to find the minimum of the sum of the differences between $y$ and $x$. So the objective function is the following:

$$\min \sum^T_{t = 0} (y_t - x_t)$$

2.D. Standard form¶

3. Solution¶

First, we import necessary packages:

In [142]:
using Plots, Distributions, Random, JuMP, Ipopt

Based on the problem we have above, we first define the time span and time delta (i.e., the size of each timestamp). Also, we know that the velocity of the planned trajectory is a function of time. To make things easier, we need to have that function ready in the beginning.

In [143]:
# the size of each time stamp is 0.2 second
delta = 0.2

# time span
T = 0.0:delta:50
Out[143]:
0.0:0.2:50.0
In [144]:
function get_vy(t)
    """This function gets the velocity of the planned vehicle
    """
    
    if t <= 10
        y_dot = 30
    elseif t <= 20
        y_dot = 30
        for i in 10+delta:delta:t
            y_dot += delta*(-2)
        end
    elseif t <= 30
        y_dot = 10
        for i in 20+delta:delta:t
            y_dot += delta*2
        end
    else
        y_dot = 30
    end
    return y_dot
end

Then we have our constraints:

In [149]:
# initial setting at the first timestamp
@constraint(m, y[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, int_y[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, vy[1] == 30)
@constraint(m, x[1] == 3)
@constraint(m, int_x[1] == 0)
@constraint(m, vx[1] == 28)

# initialize at the first timestamp
@constraint(m, ap[1] == Kp*(y[1]-x[1]))
@constraint(m, ai[1] == Ki*(int_y[1]-int_x[1]))
@constraint(m, ad[1] == Kd*(vy[1]-vx[1]))

# random error in acceleration control
# + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2))
Random.seed!(1234)
@constraint(m, a[1] == ap[1] + ai[1] + ad[1] + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2)))

# loop through timestamps:
for i in 2:N
    @constraint(m, vx[i] == vx[i-1] + a[i-1] * delta)
    @constraint(m, x[i] == x[i-1] + (vx[i] + vx[i-1])*delta/2)
    @constraint(m, int_x[i] == int_x[i-1] + x[i]* delta)
    
    # update y
    t = (i-1)*0.2
    @constraint(m, vy[i] == get_vy(t))
    @constraint(m, y[i] == y[i-1] + vy[i]*delta)
    @constraint(m, int_y[i] == int_y[i-1] + y[i]*delta)
    
    # update ap, ai, ad, and a 
    @constraint(m, ap[i] == Kp*(y[i] - x[i]))
    @constraint(m, ai[i] == Ki*(int_y[i] - int_x[i]))
    @constraint(m, ad[i] == Kd*(vy[i] - vx[i]))
    
    # random error in acceleration control
    Random.seed!(1234)
    @constraint(m, a[i] == ap[i] + ai[i] + ad[i] + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2)))
end

Our objective function:

In [150]:
# least square
@objective(m, Min, sum( (y-x).^2 ))

optimize!(m)

In order to demonstrate that the above solution is indeed optimal, we compare it with the results when k_p=2, k_i=0, and k_d=1.

In [154]:
function get_data(t, k_p=2, k_i=0, k_d=1, noise = true)
    """This function returns the trajectory of the planned vehicle (y) 
    and the actual vehicle (x)
    
    The key is that the initial acceleration of the actual vehicle can be calculated 
    through the initial state and the set parameters. Using this acceleration at t=0,
    we can calculate the velocity of the actual vehicle at the next timestamp. Then, 
    using vx, we can calculate x and int_x.
    
    vy, y, and the int_y can be calculated easily. 
    """
    # initial state
    # y for the planned vehicle, x for the actual vehicle
    
    y = 0 # position
    int_y = 0 # integral of position
    vy = 30 # speed
    x = 3
    int_x = 0
    vx = 28
    
    a_p = k_p * (y - x)
    a_i = k_i * (int_y - int_x)
    a_d = k_d * (vy - vx)
    if noise
        a = a_p + a_i + a_d + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2))
    else
        a = a_p + a_i + a_d
    end
    if t == 0
        return (y, x)
    else
        for i in delta:delta:t
            vx_prev = vx
            vx += a * delta
            # THIS IS USING APPROXIMATION!
            x += 0.5*(vx_prev + vx) * delta
            # THIS IS USING APPROXIMATION AS WELL!
            int_x += x * delta

            # update y
            vy = get_vy(i)
            y += vy * delta
            int_y += y * delta

            # update a_p, a_i, a_d, and a for usage at next timestamp
            a_p = k_p * (y - x)
            a_i = k_i * (int_y - int_x)
            a_d = k_d * (vy - vx)
            if noise
                a = a_p + a_i + a_d + rand(Uniform(-0.2, 0.2))
            else
                a = a_p + a_i + a_d
            end
        end
        return (y, x)
    end
end

5. Conclusion¶

The goal of this project is to find optimal PID controll parameters Kp, Ki, and Kd in order to minimize the sum of squares of the differences between the location of the actual vehicle and the planned trajectory. We constructed the mathematical model based on the problem descriptions and solved it using JuMP (Ipopt solver). The results seem plausible compared to the result based on random parameter setting.

For future directions, we are thinking of extending the problem to higher dimensions. Right now, we assume that vehicles move on a straight line, i.e., move only in one dimension. If the problem is set in 2 dimensions, the dynamics are much more complicated (because we can control both the direction and the volume of the acceleration) but the setting would be more realistic.
